</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,153,395]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis box="[199,433,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Taxonomic Remarks.</emphasis>
The pointy aedeagus in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[851,1015,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 196–208" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1369,1394]" captionTargetBox="[161,1376,279,1341]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1388,265,1349]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 196–208. Adelopsis bruchi (Pic, 1926), 196–201, lectotype male in MNHN, from Buenos Aires. 196, aedeagus, frontal view of aedeagus apex; 197, last ventrite; 198, antenna, dorsal view; 199, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 200, protarsus and protibia; 201, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 202–206, paralectotype male in MACN (same data). 202–205, aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views; 206, genital segment; 207–208, paralectotype female in MNHN (same data), spermatheca, in different views. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 196, 197, 202–208; b for figs. 198–201." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542809/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Figs. 202, 204</figureCitation>
), together with the frontal view of the tip of the right lobe of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[564,728,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 196–208" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1369,1394]" captionTargetBox="[161,1376,279,1341]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1388,265,1349]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 196–208. Adelopsis bruchi (Pic, 1926), 196–201, lectotype male in MNHN, from Buenos Aires. 196, aedeagus, frontal view of aedeagus apex; 197, last ventrite; 198, antenna, dorsal view; 199, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 200, protarsus and protibia; 201, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 202–206, paralectotype male in MACN (same data). 202–205, aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views; 206, genital segment; 207–208, paralectotype female in MNHN (same data), spermatheca, in different views. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 196, 197, 202–208; b for figs. 198–201." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542809/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Figs. 196, 203</figureCitation>
), seems to help in the recognition of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,153,395]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
This species is another good example to show the need to illustrate as many views of the aedeagus as possible. For instance, the pointy nature of the apex of the right lobe of the aedeagus can be observed in frontal view of the apex (
<figureCitation box="[219,316,297,324]" captionStart="FIGURES 196–208" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1369,1394]" captionTargetBox="[161,1376,279,1341]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1388,265,1349]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 196–208. Adelopsis bruchi (Pic, 1926), 196–201, lectotype male in MNHN, from Buenos Aires. 196, aedeagus, frontal view of aedeagus apex; 197, last ventrite; 198, antenna, dorsal view; 199, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 200, protarsus and protibia; 201, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 202–206, paralectotype male in MACN (same data). 202–205, aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views; 206, genital segment; 207–208, paralectotype female in MNHN (same data), spermatheca, in different views. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 196, 197, 202–208; b for figs. 198–201." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542809/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 196</figureCitation>
), but cannot be seen in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[720,817,297,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 196–208" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1369,1394]" captionTargetBox="[161,1376,279,1341]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1388,265,1349]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 196–208. Adelopsis bruchi (Pic, 1926), 196–201, lectotype male in MNHN, from Buenos Aires. 196, aedeagus, frontal view of aedeagus apex; 197, last ventrite; 198, antenna, dorsal view; 199, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 200, protarsus and protibia; 201, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 202–206, paralectotype male in MACN (same data). 202–205, aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views; 206, genital segment; 207–208, paralectotype female in MNHN (same data), spermatheca, in different views. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 196, 197, 202–208; b for figs. 198–201." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542809/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 203</figureCitation>
), which is also different from 
<figureCitation box="[1151,1230,297,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–75" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1679,1704]" captionTargetBox="[181,1400,688,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[175,1411,679,1659]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 62–75. Adelopsis orcina Szymczakowski, 1975 new status. 62–67, (probable) holotype male in CBCV, from Cueva de Camburales. 62, head, lateral view; 63, antenna, dorsal view; 64, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 65, protarsus and protibia; 66, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 67, metatarsus and metatibia; 68–69, additional male (same data). 68, last ventrite; 69, genital segment; 70–74, additional male (same data), aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views, and frontal view of aedeagus apex; 75, female (same data), spermatheca. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 68–75; b for figs. 62–67." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542781" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542781/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1202,1230,297,323]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8796" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" unit="in" value="74.0">74</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jeannel, R." box="[1264,1431,297,324]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref43714" refString="Jeannel, R. (1936) Monographie des Catopidae. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, New Series, 1, 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1936">Jeannel (1936)</bibRefCitation>
, illustrated with the adeagus slightly rocked towards its apex, in which the opening of the aedeagus appears deeper and the left lobe appears longer when compared to our 
<figureCitation box="[769,865,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURES 196–208" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1369,1394]" captionTargetBox="[161,1376,279,1341]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[151,1388,265,1349]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 196–208. Adelopsis bruchi (Pic, 1926), 196–201, lectotype male in MNHN, from Buenos Aires. 196, aedeagus, frontal view of aedeagus apex; 197, last ventrite; 198, antenna, dorsal view; 199, meso and metathorax, ventro-lateral view (of left side of specimen); 200, protarsus and protibia; 201, mesotarsus and mesotibia; 202–206, paralectotype male in MACN (same data). 202–205, aedeagus, left lateral, dorsal, right lateral, and ventral views; 206, genital segment; 207–208, paralectotype female in MNHN (same data), spermatheca, in different views. Scale lines = 0.5 mm; a for figs. 196, 197, 202–208; b for figs. 198–201." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3542809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3542809/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 203</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
